  {%- elsif ph == 'blog-streetwear-trends-india' -%}
  <article class="article-hub__article">
    <header class="article-hub__header">
      <span class="text-eyebrow">Fashion &amp; Styling</span>
      <h1>Streetwear Trends in India: Street Culture &amp; Devotion Within</h1>
      <p class="article-hub__meta">By Tokiyo Style Team · July 2026</p>
    </header>
    <div class="article-hub__image"><img src="{{ 'hero-slide-4.png' | asset_url }}" alt="Streetwear Trends India" loading="eager"></div>
    <div class="article-hub__body">
      <p>Indian streetwear has arrived. What began as a niche import culture — kids in Mumbai and Delhi wearing Supreme and Off-White replicas — has evolved into a fully-formed domestic ecosystem of brands, drops, and cultural references uniquely Indian in character.</p>
      <h2>The Rise of Desi Streetwear</h2>
      <p>Brands like Tokiyo Lifestyle are part of a new wave redefining what Indian street fashion looks like. Instead of copying Western aesthetics wholesale, we are drawing on local iconography — temple architecture, Devanagari script, classical paintings, chai culture — and remixing them through an oversized, drop-shoulder lens.</p>
      <h2>Key Trends for 2026</h2>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Oversized Silhouettes:</strong> Drop-shoulder fits with a boxy chest are the dominant aesthetic. Think chest width 2–3 inches wider than a traditional tee.</li>
        <li><strong>Graphic Storytelling:</strong> Bold front graphics are back — but now with cultural commentary. Indian mythology meets Japanese anime in the most unexpected collisions.</li>
        <li><strong>Heavyweight Cotton:</strong> The shift from 180 GSM to 240 GSM is visible everywhere. Customers want a tee that holds its structure and drapes richly.</li>
        <li><strong>Monochrome Palette:</strong> Black, white, beige, and pista dominate — with red as the single accent colour.</li>
      </ul>
      <h2>Devotion Within</h2>
      <p>One of the defining concepts in new Indian streetwear is "devotion within" — the idea that personal style is a form of self-expression and self-respect. You wear what you believe in. The streets are your runway. Tokiyo was built on this philosophy.</p>
    </div>
  </article>

