  {%- elsif ph == 'blog-why-fabric-quality-matters' -%}
  <article class="article-hub__article">
    <header class="article-hub__header">
      <span class="text-eyebrow">Fabric &amp; Quality</span>
      <h1>Why Fabric Quality Matters: The Truth About GSM &amp; Cotton</h1>
      <p class="article-hub__meta">By Tokiyo Quality Team · July 2026</p>
    </header>
    <div class="article-hub__image"><img src="{{ 'hero-slide-3.png' | asset_url }}" alt="Fabric Quality Matters" loading="eager"></div>
    <div class="article-hub__body">
      <p>If you have ever held two T-shirts side-by-side and immediately felt the difference in quality, you already understand GSM. Grams per square metre is the weight of fabric per unit area — and it is the single most important number in evaluating a T-shirt's quality.</p>
      <h2>Understanding GSM</h2>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>120–150 GSM:</strong> Very thin, transparent, budget fast-fashion territory</li>
        <li><strong>160–180 GSM:</strong> Standard mass-market T-shirt weight — acceptable but unremarkable</li>
        <li><strong>200–220 GSM:</strong> Mid-weight, good for casual wear</li>
        <li><strong>240 GSM+:</strong> Premium heavyweight — structured drape, superior durability, exceptional print quality</li>
      </ul>
      <h2>Why Tokiyo Uses 240 GSM</h2>
      <p>At 240 GSM, the fabric is heavy enough to hold its shape even when oversized — the drop-shoulder silhouette drapes cleanly rather than collapsing. It also creates the perfect surface for DTF printing: thick, tightly woven cotton holds ink at a molecular level, resulting in prints that last hundreds of wash cycles.</p>
      <h2>100% Cotton vs Cotton Blend</h2>
      <p>Polyester blends are cheaper but they pill, retain odour, and feel synthetic against skin. 100% super-combed cotton is breathable, skin-friendly, and develops a beautiful soft hand-feel over time. We never compromise on cotton purity.</p>
    </div>
  </article>

  {%- elsif ph == 'blog-dtf-printing-vs-screen-printing' -%}
  <article class="article-hub__article">
    <header class="article-hub__header">
      <span class="text-eyebrow">Fabric &amp; Quality</span>
      <h1>DTF Printing vs Screen Printing: Which is Better?</h1>
      <p class="article-hub__meta">By Tokiyo Quality Team · July 2026</p>
    </header>
    <div class="article-hub__image"><img src="{{ 'hero-slide-4.png' | asset_url }}" alt="DTF vs Screen Printing" loading="eager"></div>
    <div class="article-hub__body">
      <p>There are two dominant printing technologies in premium garment production today: Direct-to-Film (DTF) and traditional screen printing. Understanding the difference helps you appreciate the quality of the clothing you invest in.</p>
      <h2>Screen Printing</h2>
      <p>Screen printing pushes ink through a mesh stencil onto fabric. It produces vibrant, durable prints for simple designs with flat colours. However, it is expensive for complex multi-colour graphics, impractical for photographic detail, and requires minimum print quantities of several hundred units.</p>
      <h2>DTF Printing</h2>
      <p>DTF (Direct-to-Film) printing transfers a design from a film sheet to fabric using heat. It can reproduce photographic complexity, unlimited colours, and fine detail without minimum order quantities. The resulting print is soft, flexible, and highly wash-resistant.</p>
      <h2>Why Tokiyo Uses DTF</h2>
      <p>Our limited-edition drops involve complex original artwork — Japanese calligraphy, gradient elements, anime-influenced illustrations. DTF is the only technology that faithfully reproduces this level of detail. Our prints are cured at precisely controlled temperatures for maximum durability and are rated to survive 200+ washes without significant colour loss.</p>
      <h2>Puff Print</h2>
      <p>We also use puff print for select designs — a raised ink technique that adds tactile texture and three-dimensional depth to graphics. Puff prints are particularly striking on solid-colour tees where the raised graphic creates a sculptural effect.</p>
    </div>
  </article>

  {%- elsif ph == 'blog-embroidery-vs-printed' -%}
  <article class="article-hub__article">
    <header class="article-hub__header">
      <span class="text-eyebrow">Fabric &amp; Quality</span>
      <h1>Embroidery vs Printed Designs: Choosing the Right Technique</h1>
      <p class="article-hub__meta">By Tokiyo Quality Team · July 2026</p>
    </header>
    <div class="article-hub__image"><img src="{{ 'hero-slide-5.jpg' | asset_url }}" alt="Embroidery vs Printed Designs" loading="eager"></div>
    <div class="article-hub__body">
      <p>Two distinct visual languages exist in garment decoration: the tactile permanence of embroidery and the photographic flexibility of printing. Each has its place in a premium wardrobe.</p>
      <h2>Embroidery</h2>
      <p>Embroidery uses thread stitched directly into fabric, creating a raised, textured effect. It is virtually permanent — unlike prints, embroidery does not fade. It works beautifully for logos, monograms, and simple graphic elements. However, it is expensive for complex full-colour designs and adds weight to the garment.</p>
      <h2>DTF Print</h2>
      <p>Printing allows photographic reproduction at any size. A DTF print can recreate an entire painting on a T-shirt back — something embroidery could never achieve at any price point. Modern DTF printing is as durable as high-quality embroidery when properly cared for.</p>
      <h2>Our Approach at Tokiyo</h2>
      <p>We select the technique based on the design intent. Small chest logos — like the Tokiyo brand mark — work beautifully as puff print or embroidery. Large back graphics and full-front artwork are always executed in DTF for maximum detail and visual impact. The result is a garment where every element is optimised for its specific role.</p>
    </div>
  </article>

