  {%- elsif ph == 'blog-how-to-wash-printed-tshirts' -%}
  <article class="article-hub__article">
    <header class="article-hub__header">
      <span class="text-eyebrow">Care Guides</span>
      <h1>How to Wash Printed T-Shirts and Prevent Fading</h1>
      <p class="article-hub__meta">By Tokiyo Care Team · July 2026</p>
    </header>
    <div class="article-hub__image"><img src="{{ 'hero-slide-1.png' | asset_url }}" alt="How to Wash Printed T-Shirts" loading="eager"></div>
    <div class="article-hub__body">
      <p>The most common cause of graphic tee degradation is improper washing. Follow these guidelines to keep your Tokiyo prints looking fresh for years.</p>
      <h2>The Golden Rules</h2>
      <ol>
        <li><strong>Turn inside-out before washing.</strong> This is the single most important step. It protects the print from abrasion against other garments and the machine drum.</li>
        <li><strong>Use cold water only.</strong> Hot water degrades print adhesion and shrinks cotton fibres. Always wash at 30°C or below.</li>
        <li><strong>Use a gentle cycle.</strong> High-speed agitation stresses both fabric and print. Choose the delicate or gentle programme.</li>
        <li><strong>Use mild detergent.</strong> Avoid detergents with bleach or optical brighteners — they strip colour from both fabric and prints.</li>
        <li><strong>Do not tumble dry.</strong> Heat is the enemy of graphic prints. Always air dry, preferably inside-out in indirect light.</li>
      </ol>
      <h2>What to Avoid</h2>
      <ul>
        <li>Never iron directly on a print — always iron inside-out</li>
        <li>Avoid dry cleaning</li>
        <li>Do not wring the garment</li>
        <li>Keep away from direct sunlight while drying</li>
      </ul>
      <h2>Our Quality Promise</h2>
      <p>Tokiyo DTF prints are rated for 200+ washes when following our care instructions. The adhesive layer is heat-cured at a specific temperature during production to maximise longevity. With proper care, your Tokiyo graphic will remain vibrant for years.</p>
    </div>
  </article>

  {%- elsif ph == 'blog-tshirt-care-tips' -%}
  <article class="article-hub__article">
    <header class="article-hub__header">
      <span class="text-eyebrow">Care Guides</span>
      <h1>Complete T-Shirt Care Tips: Keep Your Tokiyo Looking New</h1>
      <p class="article-hub__meta">By Tokiyo Care Team · July 2026</p>
    </header>
    <div class="article-hub__image"><img src="{{ 'hero-slide-2.png' | asset_url }}" alt="T-Shirt Care Tips" loading="eager"></div>
    <div class="article-hub__body">
      <p>A well-cared-for heavyweight cotton T-shirt can last a decade or more. Here is the complete guide to maintaining the fabric, print, and fit of your Tokiyo pieces.</p>
      <h2>Storage</h2>
      <p>Fold oversized tees instead of hanging them. Hanging a heavy cotton tee on a narrow hanger stretches the neckline and shoulder seams over time. Store in a cool, dry drawer or shelf.</p>
      <h2>Washing Frequency</h2>
      <p>240 GSM cotton does not need to be washed after every wear unless there is visible sweat or staining. Over-washing shortens the lifespan of any garment. A light air-out after casual wear extends the freshness significantly.</p>
      <h2>Removing Stains</h2>
      <p>Address stains immediately — the longer they sit, the harder they are to remove. Dab (do not rub) cold water onto the stain, apply a tiny amount of liquid soap, and rinse gently. Never scrub near the printed area.</p>
      <h2>Maintaining the Oversized Fit</h2>
      <p>Cotton does not stretch back easily once deformed. Always lay oversized tees flat to dry after washing to preserve the original silhouette. Avoid machine drying at any temperature.</p>
      <h2>Neckline Care</h2>
      <p>To maintain the round-neck or ribbed collar shape, dry the garment with the neck smoothed into shape by hand. If the neckline stretches slightly over time, a careful damp hand-reshape followed by air drying usually restores it.</p>
    </div>
  </article>

