      <p>Oversized does not mean shapeless. The best oversized tees are carefully engineered — their silhouette is intentional, not accidental. Here is how to identify a well-designed oversized fit and choose your perfect size.</p>
      <h2>Key Measurements to Know</h2>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Chest Width:</strong> Measure across your chest — a well-fitting oversized tee should be 4–6 inches wider than this measurement</li>
        <li><strong>Shoulder Drop:</strong> The seam should sit 2–3 inches below your natural shoulder point for authentic drop-shoulder styling</li>
        <li><strong>Length:</strong> Should hit at or just below the hip bone — long enough to tuck partially or layer over other items</li>
        <li><strong>Sleeve Length:</strong> Mid-bicep for a relaxed oversized look, not too short to look fitted</li>
      </ul>
      <h2>The Tokiyo Fit Guide</h2>
      <table>
        <thead><tr><th>Size</th><th>Chest (inches)</th><th>Length (inches)</th><th>Shoulder (inches)</th></tr></thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr><td>S</td><td>21</td><td>28</td><td>20</td></tr>
          <tr><td>M</td><td>22.5</td><td>29</td><td>21</td></tr>
          <tr><td>L</td><td>24</td><td>30</td><td>22</td></tr>
          <tr><td>XL</td><td>25.5</td><td>31</td><td>23</td></tr>
          <tr><td>XXL</td><td>27</td><td>32</td><td>24</td></tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
      <h2>Common Mistakes</h2>
      <p><strong>Going too big:</strong> Oversized does not mean three sizes up. The ideal is 1–2 sizes above your true size. Beyond that, the garment loses structure and looks sloppy rather than intentional.</p>
      <p><strong>Ignoring the drop-shoulder seam:</strong> This is the defining feature of true oversized construction. If the shoulder seam sits at your natural shoulder point, it is a regular loose-fit tee — not an oversized cut.</p>
    </div>
  </article>

